    <entry>
      <title>DVI port</title>
      <link href="/2020/0623-DVI-port/"/>
      <url>/2020/0623-DVI-port/</url>
      
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h1>intro</h1><p>Digital Visual Interface，中文称为“数字视频接口”</p><h2>Different types of DVI</h2><p><a href="https://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/DVI" target="_blank" rel="noopener" title="go wiki"><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/DVI_Connector_Types.svg/272px-DVI_Connector_Types.svg.png" alt="DiffTypeDvi"></a></p><p><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/65/DVI_pinout.svg" alt="PINs"></p><h2>what I did:</h2><p><img src="http://img.youtube.com/vi/eUjPy1Nrgbs/0.jpg" alt="what I did"><br><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eUjPy1Nrgbs" target="_blank" rel="noopener" title="go YouTube">External🔗</a></p><h2>why it won’t work:</h2><p><a href="https://forums.tomshardware.com/threads/converting-dvi-i-to-dvi-d-by-removing-4-pins.2822259/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://forums.tomshardware.com/threads/converting-dvi-i-to-dvi-d-by-removing-4-pins.2822259/</a><br>That wont work. the Reason DVI-I to vga works is because DVI-I carries an analog signal. DVI-D does not carry an analog signal so it requires an active converter to convert the DVI-D’s digital signal into the VGA’s analog signal. Those 4 pins you think are ground are actually part of the analog signal.</p><h3>trivia</h3><p>The limit of bandwidth of both VGA and DVI cable is not enough for higher than 2560*1600@60fps, which includes 4K.</p><link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/KaTeX/0.6.0/katex.min.css">]]></content>
      
      
